50
00:02:54.860 --> 00:02:57.829
So I'd like to get started with this session.

51
00:02:57.860 --> 00:03:01.690
Our first speaker will be Dr. James Broderick, who

52
00:03:01.700 --> 00:03:05.300
is the CEO and founder of Palleon

53
00:03:05.780 --> 00:03:09.180
Pharmaceuticals, and he will be giving a talk on a

54
00:03:09.280 --> 00:03:12.820
first-in-class B7H3 targeted

55
00:03:12.829 --> 00:03:16.480
sialidase for boosting innate and adaptive anti-tumor

56
00:03:16.640 --> 00:03:18.240
immunity. So James?

57
00:03:24.420 --> 00:03:25.400
Yeah, thank you very much.

58
00:03:26.720 --> 00:03:28.980
This is an area of new biology.

59
00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:31.560
We call it glycoimmunology.

60
00:03:32.380 --> 00:03:34.750
And so what I'm going to do is I'm going to walk you through the foundational

61
00:03:34.860 --> 00:03:38.360
science, where it came from, our

62
00:03:38.420 --> 00:03:40.540
first-generation molecule, what we learned.

63
00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:44.800
Then we'll talk about the new molecule and why it's better, and where we plan to

64
00:03:44.840 --> 00:03:47.340
develop it. And then happy to answer questions at the end.

65
00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:51.700
So just big picture, checkpoint inhibitors have transformed

66
00:03:52.260 --> 00:03:52.920
oncology,

67
00:03:53.780 --> 00:03:55.560
but most patients still don't respond.

68
00:03:55.740 --> 00:03:59.720
So we see maybe up to a third of patients in many indications with

69
00:03:59.800 --> 00:04:00.480
some benefit,

70
00:04:01.580 --> 00:04:03.440
which is a huge advance, but

71
00:04:04.600 --> 00:04:05.899
there's a lot of unmet need.

72
00:04:06.700 --> 00:04:09.900
And what we see is that incremental improvements

73
00:04:10.420 --> 00:04:14.380
targeting the same old pathways keep happening over and over and over

74
00:04:14.420 --> 00:04:18.060
again. Tens of billions invested with only

75
00:04:18.101 --> 00:04:21.601
modest overall survival gains. So we got to do something

76
00:04:21.610 --> 00:04:22.110
different.

77
00:04:22.930 --> 00:04:26.480
And so what we think at Palleon is that addressing the majority of the

78
00:04:26.500 --> 00:04:30.300
non-responders is going to require a totally different distinct

79
00:04:30.820 --> 00:04:34.740
axis of immune evasion. And that's what we're going to talk about today.

80
00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:38.260
So I'd like to introduce you to the concept of tumor

81
00:04:38.320 --> 00:04:41.890
hypersialylation. These are post-translational

82
00:04:41.960 --> 00:04:45.580
modifications, glycosylation changes on tumor

83
00:04:45.600 --> 00:04:49.580
surfaces. And so what we see in cancer, actually the majority of

84
00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:52.570
the time, is cancer cells upregulate

85
00:04:53.280 --> 00:04:56.620
sialic acid-containing glycans, otherwise called

86
00:04:56.660 --> 00:04:59.700
sialoglycans, on their surface. And these are

87
00:05:00.540 --> 00:05:02.460
symbolized by these little purple diamonds.

88
00:05:03.420 --> 00:05:05.280
And there's a lot of literature on this.

89
00:05:06.180 --> 00:05:09.760
Hypersialylated glycans engage multiple sialic

90
00:05:09.820 --> 00:05:13.360
acid-dependent inhibitory pathways on immune

91
00:05:13.440 --> 00:05:15.020
cells, actively

92
00:05:16.040 --> 00:05:18.920
suppressing anti-tumor immunity.

93
00:05:19.860 --> 00:05:23.460
And this is a great new discovery, but the problem is

94
00:05:23.500 --> 00:05:27.400
conventional targeting with antibodies or small molecules can't overcome the

95
00:05:27.440 --> 00:05:31.160
redundancy. There's literally hundreds or thousands of

96
00:05:31.220 --> 00:05:34.600
variants of the sialoglycans, multiple different

97
00:05:34.640 --> 00:05:38.260
receptors that are involved. It's a many-to-many biology.

98
00:05:38.270 --> 00:05:42.080
It's almost like trying to block velcro versus blocking lock and

99
00:05:42.180 --> 00:05:42.440
key.

100
00:05:43.300 --> 00:05:46.510
And so we figured out how to make this whole area druggable.

101
00:05:48.160 --> 00:05:50.560
So just a little bit of background information.

102
00:05:50.620 --> 00:05:54.460
My co-founder, Carolyn Bertozzi, is really one of the pioneers in the field.

103
00:05:54.880 --> 00:05:58.740
She's a Nobel winner in chemistry, and she basically

104
00:05:59.340 --> 00:06:02.340
provided the first mechanistic characterization of

105
00:06:02.400 --> 00:06:05.400
sialoglycan-mediated immune suppression about a decade

106
00:06:05.460 --> 00:06:09.354
ago.And there had been a lot of support for this going back

107
00:06:09.384 --> 00:06:13.244
decades. Over 50 studies showing tumor hypersialylation

108
00:06:13.284 --> 00:06:15.834
was linked to poor outcome in over a dozen tumor types.

109
00:06:16.414 --> 00:06:19.844
And actually, in clinical practice, we actually use hypersialylated

110
00:06:20.024 --> 00:06:23.094
glycoproteins, sialylated glycoproteins, as prognostic

111
00:06:23.164 --> 00:06:26.304
markers. This is part of routine clinical practice.

112
00:06:26.364 --> 00:06:29.944
These are markers that show that, say, for instance,

113
00:06:29.984 --> 00:06:33.084
ovarian cancer is back. But nobody knew why.

114
00:06:33.724 --> 00:06:37.524
But the signal was quite robust. There was even some clinical evidence.

115
00:06:37.594 --> 00:06:41.464
There were two crazy groups back in the '70s, one in Germany, one in New

116
00:06:41.564 --> 00:06:43.794
York, that had actually experienced with,

117
00:06:44.964 --> 00:06:46.844
basically, live tumor vaccination.

118
00:06:46.894 --> 00:06:50.064
They showed better clinical results with a desialylated version.

119
00:06:50.144 --> 00:06:53.724
So there was hints that there may be sialoglycans mattered.

120
00:06:53.984 --> 00:06:57.324
They were linked to poor outcome. They may do something to the immune system.

121
00:06:57.994 --> 00:07:01.873
And then more recently, we have some human data showing that this

122
00:07:01.924 --> 00:07:04.244
is a very ripe area for development.

123
00:07:05.444 --> 00:07:08.544
So what do we do? We're doing enzymatic desialylation.

124
00:07:09.304 --> 00:07:12.944
It's the only way to overcome this redundancy of a many-to-many biology.

125
00:07:13.524 --> 00:07:17.334
And what it does is it actually positively impacts antitumor innate and

126
00:07:17.384 --> 00:07:20.564
adaptive immunity. So this framework of a cancer

127
00:07:20.604 --> 00:07:24.514
cell evading the immune system by this glycan-mediated

128
00:07:24.584 --> 00:07:27.704
mechanism, what we do is we have a drug that targets the

129
00:07:27.744 --> 00:07:31.644
tumor with the tumor targeting arm, and then the sialidase

130
00:07:31.684 --> 00:07:35.664
takes off all the sialic acid. And when that happens, all the

131
00:07:35.684 --> 00:07:39.264
neoantigens are exposed. The drag on innate immunity is taken

132
00:07:39.304 --> 00:07:43.204
away. We actually see enhanced innate and adaptive immunity.

133
00:07:43.904 --> 00:07:47.764
So we're enhancing antibody effector function by removing the sialic

134
00:07:47.884 --> 00:07:51.024
acid. We have a profound effect on pro-fibrotic

135
00:07:51.104 --> 00:07:54.824
CD163 positive M2 macrophages. We actually have paired

136
00:07:54.844 --> 00:07:57.984
biopsy experience in humans on this.

137
00:07:58.144 --> 00:08:00.124
We dropped them by 80% to 90%.

138
00:08:01.384 --> 00:08:05.284
In some cases, 100%. And then we've got a lot of experience showing that

139
00:08:05.304 --> 00:08:09.184
we're enhancing the priming and activation of new tumor

140
00:08:09.364 --> 00:08:12.924
immunity. So this is a very important

141
00:08:12.964 --> 00:08:16.384
checkpoint axis, we believe, mechanistically distinct from PD-1,

142
00:08:16.464 --> 00:08:19.924
PD-L1 blockade, potentially complementary to it.

143
00:08:21.324 --> 00:08:24.644
So we tried this in humans. We built a first-generation

144
00:08:24.724 --> 00:08:28.444
molecule we call E602. It was a human sialidase

145
00:08:28.584 --> 00:08:30.084
Fc dimer.

146
00:08:30.884 --> 00:08:33.204
People ask the question, "How could this be safe?

147
00:08:33.304 --> 00:08:37.264
You're taking off all the sialic acid in the body." But we actually had

148
00:08:37.274 --> 00:08:41.044
a high Km sialidase, which is only active where sialic

149
00:08:41.164 --> 00:08:42.164
acid is abundant.

150
00:08:43.304 --> 00:08:46.364
And this is a molecule that we had showed single agent

151
00:08:46.944 --> 00:08:50.864
preclinical activity in multiple workhorse models of

152
00:08:50.944 --> 00:08:54.644
immuno-oncology. It's comparable to PD-1.

153
00:08:54.764 --> 00:08:56.484
Actually, they're very indistinguishable.

154
00:08:56.584 --> 00:08:59.524
So we took it into the clinic, and we showed safety.

155
00:08:59.804 --> 00:09:03.264
We showed proof of mechanism. We were desialylating tumors.

156
00:09:03.784 --> 00:09:04.624
We showed the right

157
00:09:06.084 --> 00:09:09.324
cytokine profile. There was no cytokine storm.

158
00:09:09.364 --> 00:09:11.644
We were seeing almost like a checkpoint signature.

159
00:09:12.304 --> 00:09:16.044
And then this profound effect on CD163 macrophages in paired

160
00:09:16.084 --> 00:09:20.044
biopsies. But we only saw a modest clinical activity and

161
00:09:20.124 --> 00:09:21.904
only in the hypersialylated patients.

162
00:09:22.764 --> 00:09:25.904
And then what we realized was through paired biopsies, that our

163
00:09:25.944 --> 00:09:29.844
desialylation was only lasting a couple of days on tumors.

164
00:09:30.584 --> 00:09:33.984
And so we felt that this may be insufficient to sustain immune

165
00:09:34.084 --> 00:09:37.744
activation. We had seen some activity, but not enough to take it forward.

166
00:09:38.464 --> 00:09:42.044
Also, everybody wants single agent activity, and so the

167
00:09:42.164 --> 00:09:46.114
absence of this ADCC, ADCP functionality we think

168
00:09:46.144 --> 00:09:49.724
was a limitation. And then rather than killing the molecule,

169
00:09:49.944 --> 00:09:53.924
actually, we decided to take it forward in autoimmunity, where CD163

170
00:09:54.024 --> 00:09:57.804
macrophages play a huge role in the perpetuation of

171
00:09:57.824 --> 00:10:01.144
chronic inflammation and fibrosis in autoimmune diseases.

172
00:10:01.624 --> 00:10:05.594
And so we're actually in phase two in a study in membranous nephropathy around

173
00:10:05.624 --> 00:10:09.444
this biology. But what we did is we found a new place for

174
00:10:09.484 --> 00:10:12.424
this molecule, and then we figured out how to make the molecule better.

175
00:10:13.644 --> 00:10:17.604
And so what the targeting arm does, compared to

176
00:10:17.644 --> 00:10:20.224
the last one, it does several things.

177
00:10:20.304 --> 00:10:20.904
First of all,

178
00:10:21.864 --> 00:10:25.844
by having a targeting arm and a immune competent

179
00:10:25.964 --> 00:10:29.684
Fc, we get direct killing, which we didn't get

180
00:10:29.724 --> 00:10:33.344
before. The sialidase is still doing the same thing to the innate and

181
00:10:33.404 --> 00:10:37.284
adaptive immune system. We're getting the dramatic reduction in the pro-tumor

182
00:10:37.324 --> 00:10:41.254
macrophages. We're also getting enhanced priming and activation of T cells.

183
00:10:41.724 --> 00:10:45.524
And then lastly, the targeting arm, what it does is it increases the depth

184
00:10:45.624 --> 00:10:49.544
and durability of tumor desialylation to prolong the

185
00:10:49.564 --> 00:10:53.344
effects that we think were too short-lived with the first generation.

186
00:10:54.004 --> 00:10:57.764
And so where we decided to take this first was B7-H3 expressing

187
00:10:57.784 --> 00:11:01.704
tumors. So as many of you are well aware, B7-H3 is one

188
00:11:01.744 --> 00:11:05.624
of the most overexpressed tumor antigens out there across many

189
00:11:05.704 --> 00:11:09.284
tumor types. We layered onto that an analysis

190
00:11:09.424 --> 00:11:13.324
of hypersialylation. So we have a toolkit called

191
00:11:13.384 --> 00:11:17.044
Hydra that can quantify hypersialylation on tumor

192
00:11:17.124 --> 00:11:21.104
samples, and the blue diamonds are showing the percent of hypersialylation

193
00:11:21.564 --> 00:11:25.364
in these same tumor populations. So as you can see, there are many

194
00:11:25.424 --> 00:11:29.064
tumors that have both B7H3 overexpression and

195
00:11:29.104 --> 00:11:32.434
hypersialylation. So broad potential across

196
00:11:32.464 --> 00:11:36.194
multiple cancer populations. We're particularly interested in these

197
00:11:36.244 --> 00:11:39.744
ones where it's over 50% of both, notably

198
00:11:39.784 --> 00:11:41.944
ovarian, lung, and prostate.

199
00:11:43.164 --> 00:11:46.284
So our molecule is a B7-H3 targeted sialidase.

200
00:11:46.824 --> 00:11:50.764
We had the B7-H3 targeting arm. We have the active Fc,

201
00:11:51.184 --> 00:11:55.004
and we have the new next generation human sialidase, which is actually

202
00:11:55.044 --> 00:11:57.124
more potent than the first generation as well.

203
00:11:58.244 --> 00:11:59.824
Here's our peptide sequence.

204
00:12:00.864 --> 00:12:01.864
First disclosure.

205
00:12:03.004 --> 00:12:03.484
And

206
00:12:05.184 --> 00:12:06.324
what's the results on it?

207
00:12:07.544 --> 00:12:08.344
I had to show it.

208
00:12:11.048 --> 00:12:14.868
Anyway, so what's the difference between a non-targeted

209
00:12:14.888 --> 00:12:18.468
versus targeted? Here's data in a tumor model

210
00:12:18.928 --> 00:12:21.508
where we're comparing the untargeted and targeted

211
00:12:21.948 --> 00:12:25.148
desialylation depth and duration.

212
00:12:25.588 --> 00:12:29.258
So the Y-axis here is PNA. This is a lectin that measures

213
00:12:29.328 --> 00:12:33.308
galactose. When sialic acid is removed, galactose

214
00:12:33.388 --> 00:12:35.608
gets exposed, the PNA signal goes up.

215
00:12:36.048 --> 00:12:39.928
So as you can see here, we're having a dramatic increase in desialylation

216
00:12:39.988 --> 00:12:43.708
and dramatically more durable. We think this is going to make a huge

217
00:12:43.728 --> 00:12:47.038
difference. And then in terms of in vivo models, we ran several.

218
00:12:47.068 --> 00:12:50.968
Here's just one highlight showing that the targeted is dramatically

219
00:12:51.068 --> 00:12:54.768
better in this A375-bearing humanized NCG

220
00:12:54.828 --> 00:12:56.988
mouse, also compared to PD-1.

221
00:12:59.368 --> 00:13:02.928
So we felt this was a strong mechanistic rationale for

222
00:13:02.948 --> 00:13:06.588
advancing this type of molecule into human trials.

223
00:13:06.908 --> 00:13:10.708
So where do we go first? Everybody wants to see single-agent activity.

224
00:13:10.848 --> 00:13:14.548
So what we wanted to do is take an indication where there's high unmet need,

225
00:13:15.427 --> 00:13:19.378
there's an IO-responsive tumor type ideally, but where you

226
00:13:19.388 --> 00:13:21.268
could get anti-PD-1 naive patients.

227
00:13:22.128 --> 00:13:25.348
Obviously, we need a high B7H3, high hyposialylation.

228
00:13:25.388 --> 00:13:28.518
It would be great to be in one of these diseases where there's known

229
00:13:28.588 --> 00:13:31.728
correlations with hyposialylation and poor outcome.

230
00:13:32.348 --> 00:13:35.888
And so platinum-resistant ovarian cancer came to the top of the

231
00:13:35.948 --> 00:13:39.818
list. So obviously, as we all know, poor outcomes in this

232
00:13:39.828 --> 00:13:42.848
disease, you still can get anti-PD-1 naive

233
00:13:42.908 --> 00:13:46.868
patients. So there's, in many places around

234
00:13:46.888 --> 00:13:48.948
the world, limited prior IO exposure.

235
00:13:49.668 --> 00:13:53.148
90% have B7H3 expression. About

236
00:13:53.228 --> 00:13:55.168
two-thirds have hyposialylation.

237
00:13:55.328 --> 00:13:58.748
So this is a snapshot of a collection of nearly

238
00:13:58.788 --> 00:14:02.338
100 ovarian cancer patients with their hyposialylation

239
00:14:02.508 --> 00:14:06.068
scores, and roughly two-thirds have hyposialylation.

240
00:14:06.688 --> 00:14:08.188
And then in the literature, there's many

241
00:14:10.668 --> 00:14:14.318
publications describing CA125 and

242
00:14:14.368 --> 00:14:16.248
hyposialylation linked to poor outcomes.

243
00:14:16.388 --> 00:14:20.128
We think this would be the best disease to go first to

244
00:14:20.168 --> 00:14:21.428
test the hypothesis.

245
00:14:22.528 --> 00:14:26.168
So our roadmap is to demonstrate single-agent activity in that

246
00:14:26.248 --> 00:14:26.608
setting,

247
00:14:27.628 --> 00:14:31.608
but we'd like to expand into other B7H3-expressing

248
00:14:31.648 --> 00:14:35.168
hyposialylated tumors. So lung, non-small

249
00:14:35.288 --> 00:14:38.848
cell, and small cell, notably prostate, but there's many others,

250
00:14:39.388 --> 00:14:42.388
colon, many of the GI tumors, head and neck as well.

251
00:14:44.028 --> 00:14:47.708
One thing about this molecule is we've already demonstrated with the high

252
00:14:47.828 --> 00:14:50.488
KM sialidase, this is a very safe molecule.

253
00:14:51.308 --> 00:14:55.198
And so what it offers us, in contrast to ADCs, is an opportunity

254
00:14:55.208 --> 00:14:58.928
to move to first-line combinations without a major safety hit.

255
00:14:59.848 --> 00:15:03.368
We'd like to systemically expand out the platform as well

256
00:15:03.888 --> 00:15:07.608
and go after different TAA targets and then other formats,

257
00:15:07.988 --> 00:15:11.248
including T cell engagers and other bispecifics.

258
00:15:13.828 --> 00:15:17.668
So what we have is a molecule, which is the anchor

259
00:15:17.748 --> 00:15:21.608
oncology molecule out of a new platform of targeted

260
00:15:21.688 --> 00:15:25.458
sialidases, which we think is a major new way of

261
00:15:25.468 --> 00:15:29.368
going after immune evasion in solid tumors that basically

262
00:15:29.408 --> 00:15:33.308
people missed because everyone's so focused on protein targets.

263
00:15:33.788 --> 00:15:36.848
You just focus on protein targets, you're going to miss the

264
00:15:36.888 --> 00:15:39.988
post-translational modifications such as glycosylation.

265
00:15:40.628 --> 00:15:44.568
So we just didn't have the lens to see this really, and Bertozzi

266
00:15:44.668 --> 00:15:48.648
was the one that really put the light on it and

267
00:15:48.668 --> 00:15:51.328
showed how important this area of biology could be.

268
00:15:51.468 --> 00:15:54.788
So we think this is a very important axis of immune evasion.

269
00:15:55.248 --> 00:15:59.028
A lot of support now directly accessible

270
00:15:59.108 --> 00:16:00.768
through the work that we've done at Palleon.

271
00:16:01.568 --> 00:16:05.268
Our first-generation molecule did show some activity, showed

272
00:16:05.348 --> 00:16:09.258
safety and proof of mechanism, but it really helped us figure out

273
00:16:09.288 --> 00:16:12.008
what to do next. How do we get better results?

274
00:16:12.388 --> 00:16:14.808
Why weren't the results better the first time?

275
00:16:14.868 --> 00:16:18.308
And this dual idea of a

276
00:16:19.028 --> 00:16:22.758
durable tumor surface desialylation and then

277
00:16:22.848 --> 00:16:26.727
also adding the immune combinant Fc were critical innovations.

278
00:16:27.787 --> 00:16:30.068
So the new molecule satisfies both of these,

279
00:16:31.088 --> 00:16:34.948
and we're initiating a first-in-human trial with the

280
00:16:34.988 --> 00:16:38.808
safety lead-in and expansion to platinum-resistant ovarian cancer,

281
00:16:39.368 --> 00:16:41.528
as well as maybe possibly others.

282
00:16:42.608 --> 00:16:46.368
So the key takeaway here is this is a whole new category.

283
00:16:46.588 --> 00:16:49.348
We're not an ADC, we're not a checkpoint

284
00:16:49.888 --> 00:16:53.508
blocker. We're actually going after a whole new target space

285
00:16:54.008 --> 00:16:57.668
of glycosylation in cancer, and we think it's mechanistically

286
00:16:57.678 --> 00:17:01.188
distinct, potentially broadly applicable, it's

287
00:17:01.198 --> 00:17:04.797
safe, and could be the next new class of

288
00:17:04.848 --> 00:17:06.398
important cancer immunotherapies.

