356
00:21:25.848 --> 00:21:30.208
ECI-830,

357
00:21:30.248 --> 00:21:34.088
a potent and highly selective CDK2 inhibitor for treatment of

358
00:21:34.368 --> 00:21:37.868
HR-positive and HER2-negative breast

359
00:21:37.948 --> 00:21:41.728
cancer and CCNE1 amplified tumors.

360
00:21:47.208 --> 00:21:50.368
Thank you very much to the organizers for giving us this great

361
00:21:50.428 --> 00:21:53.768
opportunity to present on the discovery of

362
00:21:53.808 --> 00:21:57.728
ECI-830, which is a highly potent and selective CDK2

363
00:21:57.768 --> 00:21:59.188
inhibitor.

364
00:22:00.108 --> 00:22:01.608
So these are my disclosures.

365
00:22:02.888 --> 00:22:06.458
Now by way of a brief introduction, the cyclin-dependent

366
00:22:06.548 --> 00:22:10.098
kinases, or CDKs, play a key role in

367
00:22:10.128 --> 00:22:13.088
regulating the cell cycle. In particular,

368
00:22:13.408 --> 00:22:17.188
CDK4/6 and 2 control the

369
00:22:17.228 --> 00:22:21.038
G1 to S-phase transition when cells are committing

370
00:22:21.068 --> 00:22:24.948
to DNA replication. Now, this is occurring in a highly

371
00:22:25.048 --> 00:22:28.528
coordinated process where active cyclin

372
00:22:28.608 --> 00:22:32.487
CDK complexes will phosphorylate key substrates

373
00:22:32.668 --> 00:22:36.568
such as the tumor suppressor Rb, and this in turn will

374
00:22:36.628 --> 00:22:40.258
release the brakes on the E2F family of transcription factors,

375
00:22:40.748 --> 00:22:44.708
consequently promoting gene expression to prepare

376
00:22:44.988 --> 00:22:48.898
cells to enter the S phase. Now in cancer, this

377
00:22:48.928 --> 00:22:52.508
highly regulated network is disrupted, and an

378
00:22:52.648 --> 00:22:56.548
example of this is cyclin D. Cyclin D

379
00:22:56.628 --> 00:22:59.488
levels are strictly regulated in normal cells.

380
00:23:00.448 --> 00:23:00.808
But in

381
00:23:01.928 --> 00:23:05.828
cancer cells, cyclin D overexpression is known to be a recurring

382
00:23:05.868 --> 00:23:09.548
feature in tumors, particularly also in

383
00:23:09.608 --> 00:23:11.948
hormone receptor-positive breast cancers

384
00:23:12.908 --> 00:23:16.768
where the potential for exploiting cell cycle targeting

385
00:23:16.828 --> 00:23:20.118
has been best demonstrated with the successful

386
00:23:20.208 --> 00:23:23.868
development and application of CDK4/6 inhibitors.

387
00:23:25.688 --> 00:23:29.568
So in hormone receptor-positive breast cancers, we

388
00:23:29.608 --> 00:23:33.348
know that targeting estrogen receptor signaling with

389
00:23:33.388 --> 00:23:34.408
endocrine therapy

390
00:23:35.328 --> 00:23:37.808
is a really important part of the treatment.

391
00:23:38.808 --> 00:23:42.548
However, because estrogen receptor signaling plays a key role in

392
00:23:42.568 --> 00:23:46.268
driving and feeding into the cell cycle, combination with

393
00:23:46.328 --> 00:23:50.248
CDK4/6 inhibitors is also a key part of the treatment

394
00:23:50.288 --> 00:23:52.868
strategy. And this is demonstrated

395
00:23:53.768 --> 00:23:57.008
with ribociclib, our CDK4/6 inhibitor,

396
00:23:57.948 --> 00:24:00.408
which importantly demonstrates

397
00:24:00.548 --> 00:24:04.348
an increase in median overall survival

398
00:24:05.068 --> 00:24:08.828
in this metastatic breast cancer patient population from the

399
00:24:08.848 --> 00:24:12.612
MONALEESA trial.And so, while

400
00:24:12.672 --> 00:24:16.572
this clearly represents a very exciting and significant

401
00:24:16.582 --> 00:24:20.052
treatment advance in this space, I think we all

402
00:24:20.112 --> 00:24:23.992
appreciate that progression continues to remain

403
00:24:24.052 --> 00:24:25.211
a clinical challenge.

404
00:24:26.132 --> 00:24:30.012
And so what can we learn about resistance mechanisms

405
00:24:30.552 --> 00:24:33.802
as well as features that can influence the extent of

406
00:24:33.872 --> 00:24:36.432
response to these current treatments?

407
00:24:38.712 --> 00:24:41.912
And so we currently understand that there are various

408
00:24:42.532 --> 00:24:46.472
mechanisms that have been described in response to these treatments

409
00:24:46.532 --> 00:24:50.272
that include both genetic and non-genetic mechanisms.

410
00:24:51.052 --> 00:24:54.832
And in the class of the cell cycle alterations, what we

411
00:24:54.852 --> 00:24:58.742
know is that RB loss is a clear mechanism of

412
00:24:58.812 --> 00:25:02.372
resistance to CDK4/6 inhibitor. However,

413
00:25:02.832 --> 00:25:06.472
as we currently understand, the frequency of RB loss is

414
00:25:06.552 --> 00:25:10.292
rather modest. And this therefore suggests whether there's

415
00:25:10.332 --> 00:25:13.932
continued opportunity to further exploit this cell cycle

416
00:25:13.992 --> 00:25:15.942
targeting axis in this space.

417
00:25:16.892 --> 00:25:18.972
Now, related to this concept,

418
00:25:20.512 --> 00:25:24.052
analysis from the MONALEESA trial actually

419
00:25:24.092 --> 00:25:26.952
interestingly revealed that cyclin

420
00:25:27.232 --> 00:25:30.672
E1 was retrieved

421
00:25:31.612 --> 00:25:35.492
in a survey of prognostic modeling using baseline

422
00:25:35.832 --> 00:25:39.372
gene expression data from the MONALEESA trial.

423
00:25:39.432 --> 00:25:41.552
And to illustrate this more specifically,

424
00:25:42.632 --> 00:25:45.922
what is seen is that tumors that have

425
00:25:45.952 --> 00:25:49.812
relatively high expression of cyclin E

426
00:25:50.552 --> 00:25:53.872
in fact, do benefit from the ribociclib

427
00:25:53.972 --> 00:25:55.692
combination. However,

428
00:25:56.552 --> 00:25:59.992
the PFS benefit is less than in

429
00:26:00.032 --> 00:26:03.992
tumors that have relatively lower levels of cyclin

430
00:26:04.092 --> 00:26:05.372
E1 expression.

431
00:26:06.592 --> 00:26:10.472
And so altogether, these observations begin to suggest

432
00:26:10.532 --> 00:26:14.312
again, is there an opportunity to further target the

433
00:26:14.372 --> 00:26:15.572
cell cycle

434
00:26:16.372 --> 00:26:20.252
for deeper suppression and for improved PFS benefit

435
00:26:20.351 --> 00:26:23.672
in these HR-positive breast cancers?

436
00:26:24.752 --> 00:26:27.832
And so to further understand this in additional contexts,

437
00:26:29.212 --> 00:26:32.612
we also looked into baseline metastatic tumor

438
00:26:32.692 --> 00:26:36.572
biopsies from real-world data, in which what we

439
00:26:36.632 --> 00:26:40.232
observed is that first of all, there's several levels of

440
00:26:40.252 --> 00:26:41.772
cyclin E1 expression,

441
00:26:42.832 --> 00:26:46.812
and that cyclin E1 expression, along with

442
00:26:46.852 --> 00:26:50.472
E2F pathway gene expression, is increased

443
00:26:51.292 --> 00:26:55.072
in tumor biopsies following progression from endocrine

444
00:26:55.132 --> 00:26:57.792
therapy and CDK4/6 inhibitors.

445
00:26:59.572 --> 00:27:03.432
Now looking back into the DepMap studies, there are

446
00:27:03.492 --> 00:27:06.252
several key observations here to note.

447
00:27:07.092 --> 00:27:08.352
One is that

448
00:27:09.192 --> 00:27:12.212
tumor types that are associated with cyclin E1

449
00:27:12.332 --> 00:27:15.732
amplification, a subset, so for example, in

450
00:27:15.772 --> 00:27:19.412
ovarian, have a significantly high cyclin

451
00:27:19.472 --> 00:27:22.792
E1 expression and far higher than what is

452
00:27:22.852 --> 00:27:26.732
observed in these ER-positive breast cancer

453
00:27:26.812 --> 00:27:27.272
models.

454
00:27:28.332 --> 00:27:31.792
Now, given that cyclin E drives

455
00:27:32.092 --> 00:27:33.492
CDK2 activity,

456
00:27:34.352 --> 00:27:38.072
these tumor cell lines are also highly dependent

457
00:27:38.172 --> 00:27:41.892
on CDK2, and in fact, because of their

458
00:27:41.972 --> 00:27:45.932
really high level of cyclin E1, and the way in which they're

459
00:27:45.972 --> 00:27:49.612
wired, they're predominantly CDK2-dependent.

460
00:27:50.272 --> 00:27:54.102
Now, this is quite distinct from ER-positive breast cancer,

461
00:27:54.992 --> 00:27:58.412
where we know CDK4 is the predominant

462
00:27:58.432 --> 00:27:59.081
dependence.

463
00:27:59.892 --> 00:28:03.792
And so putting this all together, there is an extremely

464
00:28:05.412 --> 00:28:09.172
important hypothesis that has been introduced also

465
00:28:09.932 --> 00:28:13.772
by others in the field. And that is whether

466
00:28:13.782 --> 00:28:17.392
the addition of CDK2 inhibition on top

467
00:28:17.512 --> 00:28:21.392
of CDK4 inhibition can yield

468
00:28:21.432 --> 00:28:25.012
this deeper suppression of the cell cycle towards more

469
00:28:25.032 --> 00:28:28.232
durable responses in HR-positive breast cancer.

470
00:28:28.901 --> 00:28:32.472
And so clearly this has attracted a great deal of

471
00:28:32.532 --> 00:28:36.232
interest towards discovering CDK2 inhibitors.

472
00:28:36.312 --> 00:28:40.292
However, this has historically remained quite challenging

473
00:28:40.552 --> 00:28:44.032
because of the high homology among CDK family members,

474
00:28:44.452 --> 00:28:47.842
in particular CDK1, which we know is

475
00:28:47.872 --> 00:28:50.791
essential in healthy proliferating tissues.

476
00:28:51.652 --> 00:28:55.602
And so there's been a great amount of investment in trying

477
00:28:55.692 --> 00:28:59.412
to address this challenge. And so here,

478
00:29:00.152 --> 00:29:03.692
we're very pleased to share with you the discovery of

479
00:29:03.992 --> 00:29:05.232
ECI-830.

480
00:29:07.232 --> 00:29:10.952
So ECI-830 is a highly selective and potent

481
00:29:11.012 --> 00:29:12.252
CDK2 inhibitor.

482
00:29:13.192 --> 00:29:16.712
It's a type one ATP competitive orally

483
00:29:16.792 --> 00:29:19.832
available inhibitor. And as we can

484
00:29:19.912 --> 00:29:23.672
see, it has a high level of selectivity

485
00:29:23.692 --> 00:29:27.382
versus the key anti-target that I just mentioned,

486
00:29:27.932 --> 00:29:30.702
which is CDK1. And it also

487
00:29:30.712 --> 00:29:34.252
displays high selectivity against additional

488
00:29:34.492 --> 00:29:38.112
CDK family members, but also more broadly

489
00:29:38.192 --> 00:29:39.452
across the kinome.

490
00:29:43.132 --> 00:29:46.912
ECI-830 also displays the anticipated

491
00:29:46.972 --> 00:29:50.832
cellular activity, whereby there's potent suppression of

492
00:29:50.872 --> 00:29:54.832
phosphorylated Rb in cyclin E1 amplified

493
00:29:54.892 --> 00:29:55.392
models.

494
00:29:57.912 --> 00:30:00.502
And in in vitro drug property tests,

495
00:30:01.272 --> 00:30:04.712
ECI displays very good solubility,

496
00:30:05.412 --> 00:30:08.792
high permeability, and low cross-species

497
00:30:08.892 --> 00:30:12.712
clearance, altogether making for a molecule that

498
00:30:12.772 --> 00:30:16.636
has very favorable drug-like properties.Now,

499
00:30:16.856 --> 00:30:20.536
to further understand the interaction of ECI-830

500
00:30:20.736 --> 00:30:21.776
with CDK2,

501
00:30:24.516 --> 00:30:27.616
X-ray crystallography of ECI-830

502
00:30:28.516 --> 00:30:32.036
bound to CDK2 cycling E complex was

503
00:30:32.136 --> 00:30:34.956
resolved at 2.5 angstrom resolution.

504
00:30:35.656 --> 00:30:38.776
And this structure reveals some key

505
00:30:38.836 --> 00:30:42.616
interactions of ECI-830 with CDK2,

506
00:30:43.676 --> 00:30:47.636
and that also provide a hypothesis for the high level of

507
00:30:47.676 --> 00:30:50.906
selectivity that is seen versus CDK1.

508
00:30:51.916 --> 00:30:55.516
Now, zooming into this ATP binding pocket

509
00:30:56.136 --> 00:30:57.276
and drawing attention

510
00:30:58.136 --> 00:31:01.745
to this lower hinge region, which is colored in yellow,

511
00:31:02.646 --> 00:31:05.175
there are several things to note about this region.

512
00:31:05.296 --> 00:31:09.016
So in CDK2, first of all, this region contains

513
00:31:09.036 --> 00:31:12.236
residues that are unique to CDK2,

514
00:31:13.136 --> 00:31:16.596
such as the histidine 84 and the glutamine

515
00:31:16.756 --> 00:31:20.686
85. In addition, this lower hinge region is

516
00:31:20.776 --> 00:31:24.436
also far more structured and ordered in

517
00:31:24.476 --> 00:31:26.856
CDK2 than in CDK1.

518
00:31:27.696 --> 00:31:30.656
And so what this affords is an opportunity for

519
00:31:30.696 --> 00:31:34.196
ECI-830 to form multiple

520
00:31:34.716 --> 00:31:37.716
weak interactions that reinforce each other.

521
00:31:38.716 --> 00:31:39.716
And in particular,

522
00:31:40.776 --> 00:31:44.536
in terms of the different areas of the molecule, the ether

523
00:31:44.576 --> 00:31:48.476
pyrazole motif engages this lower hinge

524
00:31:48.536 --> 00:31:51.556
region through a hydrogen bond network.

525
00:31:52.416 --> 00:31:55.676
On the other side of the molecule, the lactam

526
00:31:55.736 --> 00:31:59.416
engages the well-known catalytic lysine

527
00:31:59.596 --> 00:32:02.776
33 residue, and there forms weak

528
00:32:02.916 --> 00:32:06.726
interactions through a water-bridged hydrogen bond network.

529
00:32:07.476 --> 00:32:11.376
And so the hypothesis being that these weak but multiple

530
00:32:11.416 --> 00:32:14.846
interactions are working to reinforce each other and

531
00:32:14.896 --> 00:32:18.316
selectively target and engage CDK2

532
00:32:18.336 --> 00:32:20.796
while sparing CDK1.

533
00:32:22.036 --> 00:32:25.836
In addition, this amino pyrazole

534
00:32:25.896 --> 00:32:29.556
lower hinge architecture affords improved ADME

535
00:32:29.696 --> 00:32:30.316
properties.

536
00:32:32.136 --> 00:32:35.116
Now, next, we wanted to really examine whether

